aps a variant of   Brett  .","Swedish and Norwegian: from the Old Norse personal name <i>Brattr</i> meaning ‘majestic, proud’ (also, of places, ‘steep’). See also   Bradt  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Britt was born about 1325, in Sutcombe, Devon, England as the son of John Le Brett and Mrs. Le Brett. He had at least 1 son with Ebote Branscombe."},"et":{"abt 1325–Deceased":"umbes 1325–Surnud","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1377–1404":"1377–1404","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1305":"1305","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","abt 1325":"umbes 1325","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Sutcombe, Devon, England":"Sutcombe, Devon, England"},"fi":{"abt 1325–Deceased":"noin 1325–Kuollut","1325–Male":"1325–Kuollut","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","1377–1404":"1377–1404","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1305":"1305","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","abt 1325":"noin 1325","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Sutcombe, Devon, England":"Sutcombe, Devon, England"},"fr":{"abt 1325–Deceased":"environ 1325–Décédé","1325–Male":"1325–Décédé","1335–Female":"1335–Décédée","1377–1404":"1377–1404","1305–Male":"1305–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1305":"1305","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","abt 1325":"environ 1325","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Sutcombe, Devon, England":"Sutcombe, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Britt est né environ 1325, à Sutcombe, Devon, Angleterre, fils de John Le Brett et Mrs. Le Brett. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Ebote Branscombe."},"de":{"abt 1325–Deceased":"um 1325–Verstorben","1325–Male":"1325–Verstorben","1335–Female":"1335–Verstorben","1377–1404":"1377–1404","1305–Male":"1305–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1305":"1305","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","abt 1325":"um 1325","